subSubSection.paragraph:
Antennae with scape and pedicel yellowish brown (Fig. 
10G
), flagellum light brown (Fig. 
10G
); pronotum yellowish brown (Fig. 
11A-D
); abdomen dark brown, with sternites VI-VIII translucent (Figs 
9A
, 
12E
), pygidium dark brown with a translucent posterior line (Fig. 
12F
); antennae with 32-41 antennomeres (Fig. 
10G
); antennomere III with flabellum 2 
x
longer than antennomere III; antennomere III as long as scape (Fig. 
10G
); maxillary apical palpomere 10 
x
longer than III (Fig. 
10A, B
); hypomeron as long as tall (Fig. 
11C
); sternite VIII with posterior margin bisinuate, central 1/3 slightly shorter than posterolateral angles (Fig. 
12E
); lanterns occupying almost the entire area of sternite VI and VII (Fig. 
9A
).

One hundred forty-six individuals were collected in hilly areas of the Ilha Grande State Park (Fig. 
1
) between 160-660 m a.s.l. in 2017 and 2018. The highest abundance was observed between 160-170 m a.s.l. This species has a continuous blue-green glow. Males fly between 0.1 and 4 m above ground level, bending their abdomens downward, possibly to light the ground in search of females, (as in other 

Amydetes

spp.; 
Vaz et al. 2021
); they sometimes flying upwards towards the forest canopy. They are apparently active in the first hours of complete darkness. About 5-10 males were observed flying together in the same visual field.

